The IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos—Lagarde said she is open to serving another five years as the Managing Director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should remain in her post.
The IMF has never had better leadership than her; the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, assuming leadership of an institution facing severe crises.
The 2008 global financial collapse and its economic aftermath tarnished the reputation of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF restore its reputation.
Many eyes were on her personal qualities—after all.
She admitted, was strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries who met with her (often in delicate settings) repeatedly expressed that she was bold in speaking the difficult realities while also being a sensitive listener.
These qualities are particularly important for a leader of an institution that must negotiate the terms of agreements rather than dominate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else they must establish firewalls to prevent financial contagion. The advice was harsh but Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she strongly advocated for IMF support to certain countries—such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine—which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation and is usually not passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this often harsh-prescriptive institution a humane face.
For example, helping manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its program to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people reside in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak erupted in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to grant debt relief to affected countries, allowing them to improve the treatment of doctors and nurses—this was the first time the IMF had used its own capital in such a manner.
In addition, Lagarde recognized the three most important challenges facing the world today and took action accordingly.
First, she forcefully advocated for increasing the participation of women in the workforce, serving as a role model for the value of having women in leadership positions.
In a variety of countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a huge talent resource—and thereby realize economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not merely a matter of basic fairness.
The IMF's research emphasizes a direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its position makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde personally has been committed to promoting this, which was key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde played a significant role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change—some of which could cause alarming destructive effects.
For example, automation will continue to improve the efficiency of manufacturing and reduce its costs, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be less than in the past.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics will argue that it is time for a representative from a developing country to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is already the eleventh European to hold this position in a row, and Europe's possession of such a privilege is already difficult to justify in today's world.
Some people might argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded significant results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some might also point out that she faces allegations linked to a financial scandal in France, which could distract her from her work at the IMF.
Following the scandal involving her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn, critics argue that the IMF must never again be distracted by similar incidents.
Let us examine each of these objections in turn.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But the purpose of ending this Western privilege is to base the selection process on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice for IMF Managing Director, and emerging powers such as the BRICS countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not jointly nominated an alternative candidate.
The appointment of a European as IMF Managing Director might have been one of the favorable factors behind the IMF's decision last December to include the renminbi in the basket of currencies that determines the value of its special drawing rights.
In addition, Lagarde demonstrated impressive political flexibility, ultimately persuading both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve IMF governance reforms. These reforms not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the evolving dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries are now among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the issue of Greece, Lagarde made some blunt — some might say inappropriate — remarks last year.
But she is not the culprit who brought economic pain to the Greeks; during her IMF tenure, she has fully demonstrated that no IMF Managing Director in history has done as much as she has to lead the IMF in alleviating the suffering of people in crises.
Finally, the French prosecution opposed the charges against Lagarde, and she was at most minimally involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has demonstrated that she is precisely such a leader, committed to making the IMF adapt to the twenty-first century.
She deserves the opportunity to see her mission through to the end.
